      "ESSeqNum": 3,
      "FacilityID": 1000106811,
      "SummaryText": "ve been no accidents meeting the Five-year Accident History criteria (per 40CFR68.42) at Heber 1.  \nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM  \nHeber staff are not First Responders. Employees are trained to evacuate and call 911 in case of an emergency. Heber coordinates with local Fire Department and First Responders. Heber has filed a Hazardous Materials Business Plan (which contains the Emergency Response Plan) to help coordinate with local responders. \n \nAn Emergency Action Plan (EAP) that meets the requirements of the CCR Title 8 3220 is in place. \n \nEXTERNAL EVENTS ANALYSIS INFORMATION \nPursuant to the requirements of California Health & Safety Code, Title 19, Division 2, Chapter 4.5, 2745.7(q); the following external events analysis information were reviewed and are submitted with the CalARP documentation:\u202f \n\u2022\tThe types of natural and human caused external events considered in PHA Section 2760.2.\u202f \no\tDuring the PHA a broad list of external events was considered by the Team. General events external to the plant that can conceivably cause a release of isopentane were addressed. The External Events that were considered are detailed within the PHA worksheets, which are included in the CalARP document. \n\u2022\tA seismic assessment of piping and equipment was performed in December 2018 and documented in a February 2019 report. \nPLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY \nThe Process Hazard Analysis (PHA) study has been conducted to examine mitigation measures to improve safety at the facility. Planned changes to improve safety are listed as recommendations made during the revalidation of the PHA for OEC 12&14, development of the PHA for OEC 1&2 and OEC 11 and the performance of the Triennial Compliance Audit in 2022.  Any outstanding recommendations will be addressed by December 2023."
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 2,
      "FacilityID": 1000106811,
      "SummaryText": "ios are also displayed in the graphic file attached to the RMP eSubmit document. \nRISK CONSIDERATIONS \nAlthough the use of isopentane has inherent potential risks, and worst-case and alternative-case release scenarios can potentially reach public receptors; Heber has recognized these potential risks and structured its safety programs to make these scenarios improbable.  \nThere are numerous facility safeguards that serve to minimize the potential risks associated with an isopentane release, which include:  \n\u2022\tAutomatic and Manual Shutdown Systems that enable remote isolation and depressurization of the OEC\u2019s and electrical isolation. \n\u2022\tAdequately Designed Pressure Relief System to provide a fail-safe backup to prevent over-pressurization \n\u2022\tPerimeter Fire Water Monitors and Storage Tank Deluge Systems to enable equipment cooling and prevent premature component failure. \n\u2022\tFlame and gas detection monitoring which interlocks with plant automatic shutdown systems and provides local audible and visual alarms. \nACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM \nAs part of the implementation of the accidental release prevention programs, prevention program elements are documented and implemented by the Heber facility to manage process safety issues associated with the use of isopentane. In addition, common industry standards, policies, and procedures are utilized to ensure safe practices are being performed. \nEach of the facility\u2019s three processes exceeds the 10,000 lb regulatory threshold quantity of isopentane.  As a result, each process is subject to CalARP Program Level 3, EPA RMP Program Level 3, OSHA PSM and Cal/OSHA PSM. \nThe Prevention Program 3 elements include:  \n\u2022\tProcess Safety Information \n\u2022\tProcess Hazard Analysis \n\u2022\tOperating Procedures \n\u2022\tTraining \n\u2022\tMechanical Integrity \n\u2022\tManagement of Change \n\u2022\tPre-Startup Safety Review \n\u2022\tCompliance Audits  \n\u2022\tIncident Investigation  \n\u2022\tEmployee Participation  \n\u2022\tHot Work Permit \n\u2022\tContractors \nFIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY \nThere ha"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
