      "SummaryText": "r-cooled shell and tube heat exchangers or air-cooled finned tube condensers and then returned to the process in a closed loop cycle.  The electric power generated by this cycle is then sold to contracted off-takers.  \nA total of five OEC\u2019s exist in the facility: OEC 12 \u2013 commissioned in 2008, OEC 14 commissioned in 2018, OEC 1&2 I3LU \u2013 commissioned April 2023, and OEC 11 \u2013 scheduled to be re-commissioned in the third quarter of 2023.  A smaller OEC, OEC 13 has been decommissioned.  The five OEC\u2019s are grouped into three processes due to their relative locations and interconnectivity.  Process 1 consists of OEC 12, 14 and two storage tanks.  Process 2 consists of OEC 1&2 and a third storage tank.  Process 3 consists of OEC 11 and a fourth storage tank. The maximum intended inventory of isopentane in the three processes is 1,167, 246 lbs., which includes the quantity charged to all five OEC\u2019s plus some residual quantity kept in storage.  The intent is to minimize the amount kept in storage to ensure adequate capacity for process evacuation during maintenance activity. \nThe site is currently operated by Heber staff and is staffed 24 hours a day. The facility employs approximately 32 personnel. \nHAZARD ASSESSMENT SUMMARY/OFFSITE CONSEQUENCE ANALYSIS \nWorst-Case Release Scenario Results Summary \nScenario Description: The worst-case release scenario is defined by the release of the contents of the OEC 2 Level 3 vaporizer.  A similar release from the OEC 14 Level 2 vaporizer or the most northern of the storage tanks (in a full condition) would result in the same impact zone.  The worst-case release can potentially impact offsite public receptors in a local residence and on adjacent agricultural land.  The most stringent prevention program requirements are applied at Heber 1.   \nAlternate Release Scenarios Results Summary \nScenario Description: An alternate release scenario was modeled as well.  Public receptors can